{{Infobox scientist |name = Graham Johnson |image = File:Graham Johnson2.jpg |caption = Johnson 2014 |image_size = 250px |birthname = Graham Johnson |birth_date = 1973 |birth_place = Ohio |alma_mater = Joppatowne High School, St. Mary's College of Maryland (B.A.), Johns Hopkins School of Medicine (M.A.), The Scripps Research Institute (PhD in Biology with a Biophysics track) |doctoral_advisor = Arthur Olson TSRI |known_for = Medical illustration, NSF Predoctoral Fellowship, NSF and Science Magazine Scientific Visualization Challenge, Computational Biology, and Scientific Visualization |prizes = }}
'''Graham Johnson''' is an [[animator]], [[illustrator]] and, beginning in 2012, [[Research fellow|faculty fellow]] at the [[California Institute for Quantitative Biosciences]].<ref name="marx2015" /> He has a [[master's degree]] in [[medical illustration]] from [[Johns Hopkins School of Medicine|Johns Hopkins]],<ref name="pdbinterview" />{{efn|Specifically, a degree in Medical and Biological Illustration from the Department of Art as Applied to Medicine.}} and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[biophysics]] from [[The Scripps Research Institute|Scripps]].<ref name="marx2015" /><ref name="pdbinterview" /> After graduating from Johns Hopkins and while working at the [[Salk Institute for Biological Studies|Salk Institute]], he illustrated the [[textbook]] ''Cell Biology''.<ref name="marx2015" /><ref name="pdbinterview" />{{efn|''Cell Biology'': See {{OCLC|70284432}}}}
Johnson is the creator of the software applications "autoPACK" and "cellPACK" which enable modeling, simulation and visualization of [[Mesoscopic physics|mesoscopic]] three-dimensional [[spatial data]] utilizing [[Packing problems#Packing in 3-dimensional containers|packing algorithms]].<ref name="marx2015" />
